<h2>The Practical Path</h2>

<p>The Eastern tradition is quite practical about how a person pursues theosis.</p>

<p><strong>The sacraments</strong>, especially the Eucharist, regularly received. The primary vehicle of theosis, the "medicine of immortality."</p>

<p><strong>Prayer</strong>, daily, structured, persistent. The Jesus Prayer is the backbone, but the tradition includes morning and evening prayers, the Psalms, and liturgical worship.</p>

<p><strong>Fasting.</strong> Not punishment but training. Fasting teaches the body that it is not in charge, creating space for the spirit to grow.</p>

<p><strong>Repentance and confession.</strong> Regular diagnosis and treatment of spiritual illness. Not a one-time event but a lifelong habit.</p>

<p><strong>Community.</strong> Theosis does not happen in isolation. It happens in the Church, in relationship with other struggling, growing Christians.</p>

<p>Theosis is not a destination. It is a direction. The Eastern Church believes every human being, in every circumstance, is invited to begin.</p>

<h2>Further Reading</h2>

<p>Kallistos Ware's <em>The Orthodox Way</em> provides the most accessible introduction to theosis in English. Vladimir Lossky's <em>The Mystical Theology of the Eastern Church</em> is more demanding but essential. For Maximus the Confessor specifically, see Lars Thunberg's <em>Microcosm and Mediator</em>. The catechism <em>Christ Our Pascha</em> treats theosis pastorally in §§ 218–232.</p>

